A Republican strategy to counter Obama’s re-election
Republican leaders justify their policies with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth, affirming that election fraud in the US is less frequent than the number of people killed by lightning.
By the way, in 10 years, Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partly undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for holding the elections in the individual states.
In this sense, the majority of American governments have since 2009 promulgated new laws that make the process of registration or ballot more difficult.
This phenomenon has gained in importance after the November 2010 elections, with 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, limiting the exercise of voting rights in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the time limits for early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on election day, and deny citizens the right to vote for which a court file is available.
Before the 2006 elections, no US state asked voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Law in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states forcing voters to show a photo ID.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a card.
However, more than a hundred dollars are often to be paid to get the required ID.
The new restrictions have disproportionately affected young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of those with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
This is even more important.
Students who are regarded as voters who vote more for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs to vote more strongly for the republican side to use the tickets issued by these clubs for elections.
Before 2004, no state requested proof of citizenship for voting.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws demanding voters to demonstrate their US citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting hispanic votes.
For it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican legislators promoted laws in eight states that abolished the registration of voters on election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to assist those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, campaigns to register voters in the 2004 general elections have helped to register around 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the proportion of new voters registered in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, although they accounted for only 13% of the state's voters.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
By contrast, the whites, representing 76% of voters, accounted for only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several bills were blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make the exercise of the right to vote more difficult.
Democratic critics denounce the party-political nature of the adopted laws and see them as a clear goal of influencing the results in the states that are crucial for 2012.
A report by the Brennan Center in 2011 shows that those states that have passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required on the electoral panel to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the electoral system legislation will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partly undermine the democratic system of the United States.
