The Higgs boson analyzes
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson last summer caused a certain stir, and for good reason.
Indeed, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or "at least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but data is still missing to be completely safe about it.
Nevertheless, let us assume that it is actually the Higgs, since there seems to be only a small risk of being deceived, and let us look at what it is about.
There is an inevitable law in this world that causes two objects not to be present at the same time in the same place.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try too hard as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that for them, too, such a law applies: the Pauli principle of exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state", whereby this "state" consists by and large of some of its properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons, a vicious gang of anarchists who are not sacred to anything - definitely not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups according to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley laboratories (which by the way is absolutely amazing): the mesons we will not treat here and the "force particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
It must be emphasized here, however, that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, it is only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
In fact, if a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" at that exact place, roughly like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbation" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
Stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" for this boson to show up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little similar to a frozen pond whose surface could only be torn apart by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator like CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interacting with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don't - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on to the refrigerator by itself.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon) have no mass.
What can all these researches be "good" for, Mrs Plamondon asks?
For science, they are used to verify the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to closely examine all deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes of the model.
It must be said that the latter still has great shortcomings, since it does not explain gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found in CERN.
Impact
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there are none.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the laser pioneers in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first continuous stroke laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already said that the laser at the beginning was rather regarded as a "laboratory game".
Imagine...
In addition, applications may also result from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, during his work in optics, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras worldwide and awarded it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you really can never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die...
With its Committee on Dignity, Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
Prostate cancer, which consumed him, had given him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in Victor-Gadbois' home for palliative care in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped with food.
Bravely he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medication, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to heal my diarrhea, as this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man pees standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
Returning to childhood is unacceptable humiliation for certain persons.
"This depends on the person's ability to take a step backwards," he notes.
In the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great events take place in the midst of these regressions.
The patients who are admitted to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, the doctors and nurses who take care of them no longer overload them with so-called "healing" care.
For Mrs. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
But the disease really made me meet my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more desires in life," she says, before accepting that she is put on a mask that helps her breathe.
In the next few days she is still expecting a last visit from her son, who comes from Italy.
The home Victor-Gadbois offers a group of volunteers body care and help with food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec there is a bed for palliative care for 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little, considering that one day we'll all die.
Here life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given oral care with brandy or pepsi as desired.
Diabetic patients no longer need to control their blood sugar level.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning, his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients alike," reports nursing director Nathalie Savard.
In the home Victor-Gadbois is no day like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years of age who enjoys the last family reunion in the yard and is well supported by his pillows as one toasts in his honor, a young man of 36 who is surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two small children dies tragically after he has tried everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients less than 45 years of age," says Dr. Christiane Martel with concern.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care intended to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as Home Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Domestic Palliative Care in Greater Montreal, are more or less exclusively specializing in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in Quebec health care that makes sure that several doctors specialised in palliative care look forward with concern to the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent figures in palliative care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not efficient enough to ensure that all have the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to go to euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who had been in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain without any action being taken to alleviate her.
I fear that patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients hard until the last day despite the worst forecasts.
The chances of survival of Hélène Richard were already minimal when she stopped an arduous chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she answered me that she was sorry that I was giving up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not accepting this wish after their pain has been alleviated by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care in the Montreal area, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which results in the patient being either sporadically or permanently put to sleep until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the possibility to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not alleviated all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to put me to sleep," but "I want my pain to be relieved."
