Other road construction officials have admitted that they were lubricated by artificially inflating the bills with false additional services by 30-40%.
In addition, an organizer of the Mayor's Party, Martin Dumont, accused Mr Tremblay of deliberately overlooking a shadow budget that filled his funds with black money.
As a result of these revelations, Mr Tremblay resigned at the beginning of November, which plunged Montreal into a severe crisis.
Chantal Rouleau was one of the first members of Montreal to sound the alarm.
As mayor of the Rivière-des-Prairies district, in the east of the island, from 2010, she refused to sell a municipal property that was purchased for $5 million and resold for 1.6 million to developers in the booming real estate market.
70% black money in election campaigns
From the investigation that is ultimately being carried out, she says that she "draws on a thread that allows us to understand the functioning of the ants-infiltrated system in order to stop the evil and denounce the culprits."
She says that the procedure is "painful but positive".
We are in the process of cleaning up the wound, but we need an investigation unit for Montreal only, as well as supervision to prevent a return of questionable practices.
How to clean up.
Regularly.
Jacques Duchesneau notes that "officials have stolen several hundred million dollars", but he is particularly concerned about the role of "mandates who are aware of the tactics" if they were not involved in the fraud!
Based on a 70% share of black money in the funding of the Quebec election campaigns, he jokes: "I was told that this was just a weak slip of reality."
The Quebec government proposes to limit the donations to parties to 100 dollars, which according to him would not change the situation: "Until campaign spending is strictly limited, black money will be in circulation in politics."
He recommends a complete overhaul of the public procurement system and the financing of the parties: "We cannot go deeper; by getting to the bottom of things with courage, we can rebuild the house on a more solid basis with more controls and laws."
If this story damages the international reputation of Quebec and Montreal, Mr Duchesneau calls on those who laugh to take a look at their own backyard...
