Fast food and supermarket workers strike in the US
One in four American youths sits behind the counter of Mc Donald's
In recent days there have been massive protests across the US against low wages in Walmart stores and restaurants of popular fast food chains such as Mc Donald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
No one can yet predict whether the protests will swell even further or whether they will soon run out of air again.
The protests are supported by trade unions and several left-wing non-profit organisations.
In addition to raising the modest wages of ordinary Walmart and fast food workers, the organizers of the protests aim to establish trade unions.
So far, this sector of the economy has hardly been organized as a trade union.
46 cents a year?
The protests started last week after Thanksgiving, the so-called Black Friday, where sales took place in the United States, attracting millions of customers, which sometimes led to handcuffs.
On that day, some Walmart employees, of whom there are 2.2 million worldwide, quit their jobs and striked along with trade unions and left-wing activists branches of the chain whose target groups are low- and middle-income individuals.
Walmart sells all products, from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The goods in the Walmart stores are on average between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
Therefore, many of the marginally paid Walmart employees buy only at their own workplace.
The prices and the product range made Walmart one of the largest companies in the USA.
According to critics, Walmart can often sell the goods so cheaply only because the employees are poorly paid.
The latter also complain about heavy working conditions, for example missing forklift trucks or hand scanners.
The protesters on "Black Friday" demanded wage increases and expressed their anger that the contribution to the company's health insurance had risen from 30 to 100 dollars a month.
A typical Walmart employee who earns $9.5 an hour cannot afford this increase, they said.
Researchers from California University in Berkeley prove that if the company raised the average wage to $12 an hour, it would cost Walmart $3.2 billion.
That's about 1.1% more than they're now donating to pay.
If Walmart were to fully convert the wage increases to customers, every purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
That would be $12.39 a year for them compared to today's additional spending.
Proponents of Walmart are pleased to note that only nine states have protested and that they have not caused any losses to the company.
The Black Friday lasted the next day in its store from 8 o'clock in the evening on Thursday to midnight, and during this period Walmart sold about 5000 items per second.
In total, the Walmart cash registers carried out almost 100 million transactions on "Black Friday".
The company's spokesman, Dan Fogelman, claimed in an interview on the website of the left-wing Huffington Post that a total of "less than five" Walmart employees dropped out of work and the protest action was merely "another PR trick" of the union that organized the protests.
"Free cash register!"
The protests continued this week in New York, where their goal was not Walmart stores (which are not wanted in this progressive city and are therefore so far nonexistent), but McDonald's and other low-priced restaurants.
McDonald's says the company's selling billions of portions, and yet you're not getting sick days, and you're not getting paid for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, Member of the New York City Council
Under federal and New York legislation, the minimum wage is currently $7.25 an hour.
In fast food restaurants, the minimum wage is gradually raised, but not too strong, and on average their simple employees in New York get 8.90 US dollars an hour.
Less than she earns no one in this expensive city.
How it is possible to get along with so little money in New York is incomprehensible to me.
There was once a time when almost a quarter of all American youths were behind the counter at McDonald's after school, but the youths still lived with their parents.
Hardly anyone saw it as the main source of income or planned to stay there for longer.
Now, in interviews with McDonald's employees, I constantly meet people who complain that they have to get along with this salary and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, there is a comment in the Wall Street Journal forum, the author of which notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know how to feed them.
Participants in the protests, which began on Thursday at 6.30 a.m. in front of McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and chefs of fast food restaurants receive a minimum wage of $15 an hour, which is more than a doubling of the current minimum wage.
They continued to demand the formation of trade unions in the fast food industry.
The U.S. law forbids corporate management to stand in the way of this goal and to call off or dismiss union members.
On the other hand, management does not make it easy for them.
However, the creation of trade unions in the fast food industry is also difficult for objective reasons.
The most important reason is the high staff turnover.
Unsatisfied
There were loud protests that day in front of many other fast food restaurants in Manhattan.
The highlight of the protests was a meeting at noon before McDonald's in Times Square, where some local Democrats spoke, including City Councillor Jumaane Williams, who said, "McDonald's says it's selling billions of portions, and yet you're not being given sick days, and you're not being paid for your honest work!"
The demonstrators were also supported by other prominent New York Democrats, for example, mayoral candidate Bill De Blasio, who said that "we should work together to support the fast food workers so that they can get a fair wage and achieve the economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves!".
According to the New York Times, this was the biggest action of its kind in the history of the U.S. fast food industry.
However, only a few hundred people were there, of whom not all are employed in the fast food industry, where tens of thousands work in New York.
It is not yet foreseeable whether the spark of these protests will mobilize entire masses.
"The brain is only moderately outsmarted so far"
The theme of enlarged reality, popular with followers of modern technologies, has been commonly perceived recently by the lens of special glasses.
At first, Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, and then in November it became known that Microsoft had also applied for a corresponding patent.
In conversation with the head of the interactive 3D technology group at the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge Shahram Izadi, it becomes clear, however, that the glasses were only a through station for the company's scientists.
It excites the possibility to manipulate virtual objects in the air with bare hands and to create virtual open spaces.
- Please give a brief description of the research your group is doing.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but want to expand the limits of this interaction.
So far, mankind has largely been stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes also touched.
However, we want to anticipate 5-10 years and foresee the radical changes of this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are progressing, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What else can we expect in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought interaction to a physical level, much is still happening on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) has been improved, the output has not yet been decisive.
We are trying to change this, working on real three-dimensional imaging systems based on different technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
However, it is necessary that not only the user but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could easily complement the real world with virtual objects.
And first of all, we should get rid of these stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
She's popular, but isn't she overrated?
- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, since it raises questions about privacy, because one does not always want to inform all bystanders about his actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the area of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project in which we experimented with short and short gestures instead of unloading gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a watch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed types of control, such as gestures and language.
- How so?
We'd like to ask you, for example, to hand you this bubble can?
They say it and at the same time point to it.
- I usually just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does that mean that you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and cannot do at the time?
- Not necessarily, but it's about mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will have to work mainly on the development of new types of sensors, which will enable people to capture reactions more accurately.
These can be laser sensors, for example, as they offer good resolution at depth, which is very important.
- What requirements do you place on modern cameras based on your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or anything else?
- The present generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixel itself, but the quality of the matrix and depth.
From this point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of algorithms have more work to do.
Not only the resolution along the X- and the Y-, but also along the Z-axis must be taken into account.
The speed and number of images per second are also important.
The movements of man are extremely dynamic and frankly, the present 30 fps are too little especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor in our Redmond laboratory with a adjustable processing delay of between 1 and 100 milliseconds, with today's commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction between man and machine.
For my work, I needed just such a device, only without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second is a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the depth of the object.
More cameras could possibly solve the problem...
Or amplify the problem, as more calculations would be necessary.
It would be nice to have a flexible, Kinect-like system in which we could play with different camera angles to see how this helps us to determine a position in three-dimensional terms.
- If I remember correctly, unlike Google, Microsoft did not present its glasses to the public.
Do you not think that with regard to the application of the technology of enlarged reality in everyday life, the glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it's not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in the raised hand on the way, but I think this: The greatest variant would be a "changing" expanded reality in which we could switch from glasses to smartphones via a cloud.
The glasses are a personal gadget and that's their strength (only you can see private things), but at the same time their weakness, because an expanded reality with glasses prevents you from working on virtual objects together with others.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is not only accessible to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point to: there is no tangible response!
The hands don't feel anything!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures, I often talk about the fact that the expanded reality represents the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection document.
She perceives pressure excellently!
But there are also technologies that are actually aimed at giving the "images in the air" something tangible, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound beams at a certain point where the finger is located creates a feeling that is at the moment however weak, as if someone blew over the hand bales.
There are also bands for the wrist that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, also this is a potential direction.
- Have you tried to outsmart the brain?
Make it think that it feels what it should feel when it's seeing something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried yet.
Here is another task that we will have to struggle with for a long time, namely to make a person physically in a closed room believe that he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), mobile platforms and large spheres.
So far, the brain is only moderately outsmarted, and we still have many busy years ahead of us.
This is precisely what makes working in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: We are only at the beginning of many topics.
