Birth in Space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earth dwellers on board are searching for a replacement planet.
In order to save mankind, the important question arises as to how we can reproduce in weightlessness or on the substitute planet?
I do not think there are many choices.
De facto, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"In other words, Mars and Venus," says the research associate of the Astronomical Sternberg Institute Vladimir Surdin.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, the surface of Venus has a temperature of 500 degrees.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The researchers first discussed the question of reproduction in space in terms of flora.
Experiments with plants were already carried out half a century before.
The fourth generation of peas bred in orbit did not differ in the least from the terrestrial species.
It followed the breeding of insects, more precisely tiny fruit flies (drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979 quail eggs were sent into space to investigate the effect of weightlessness on embryo development.
A normal chick develops.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick must find a hold; it must be able to stand on its feet and begin to move," explains the laboratory manager of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Vladimir Sychev.
Without a solid underground, the chicks wildly overturned.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely dulled.
The chicks did not react to light and sounds.
Four days later, they simply died.
"We let chicks hatch twice and then set the whole thing up because it is simply impossible to work with them there," Vladimir Sykhev notes for the failed experiment with chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, only same-sex species will be present on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized into space.
In principle, nothing special was noted.
"It was just with the biosatellites, but again it was only a single experiment, and the research needs to be continued," Vladimir Sykhev notes.
After the landing, the space rats got offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not yet been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn from their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
Unlike animals, man could do that in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
For ethical reasons, such experiments are not carried out.
But women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was with Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing humanity has is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on earth could have answered the following question: Does it survive space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"Finally, no one answered this question," says Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just a year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The father of the child, Andriyan Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988 the second woman in space, Svetlana Sawizkaja, who was in orbit twice and even did work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, there is still a risk.
We have very few cosmonauts, where after long flights everything went well and they got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is, even on flights into orbit," concludes cosmonaut Valeri Polyakov, a hero of the Soviet Union and a hero of the Russian Federation.
And yet humanity must search for new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravity.
The hydrolaboratory in the cosmonaut preparation centre is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here in a floating state, the cosmonauts gain routine for working in open space.
The water represents weightlessness.
Even if adults feel that water is pleasant, it is a foreign environment, but infants feel that water is a natural element.
It's like the little Ichtyanders testify that life on the land escaped from the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is in the womb of the mother in amniotic fluid for about 9 months and the fact that it can easily get used to water.
In principle, this is logical, since from birth until the first swim only two weeks pass.
"This is too little time to forget something," says baby swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
While weightlessness is a much more natural condition for a newborn child, the woman does not survive without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles are rapidly receding and thus the ability to push the child out decreases.
All right, let's avoid this with birth-inducing aids.
For example, the birth could also take place in a special chamber to push the child out.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Valeri Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the gravity of the earth, the organism cannot train the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put into a strain suit in orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply lack what is of fundamental importance for his life.
"This experiment, which we are undertaking together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the birth of a disabled person, a completely unadapted person," predicts Igor Pestov, head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN.
So far, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
Eventually, however, it becomes a reality when the Earth's inhabitants set off in their spaceships to a distant planet that becomes the home of their offspring born in space.
NKÚ Chief: Control of the black system fails due to political fault
The Czech Republic has good supervisory authorities and adequate laws in connection with public contracts, but falls back on their application.
In a conversation for Aktuálně.cz, the Vice-President of the Supreme Control Office (Nejvy
"A law is never perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and I do not think this is the case with us," Kala comments on the current situation.
A similar result appears to be a joint control by Czech and German auditors.
As a negative practical example, he cites the attitude of Prime Minister Petr Nečas to the so-called "black system".
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not harass businessmen with controls - is the system now banned or allowed?
"A law must be valid, and if something is prohibited by law, then it is not easy for the head of the government to come, and the control office, whose duty is to check compliance with the law, to hinder its activity," Kala notes.
At the meeting of the Supervisory Committee of the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint Czech-German project in which the laws of both countries concerning public contracts were compared.
What exactly was that all about?
This is a parallel test that we started about two years ago.
To put it simply, it is a question of the European legislature defining how public contracts are to be handled, on which national legislation builds, and finally, there is the actual practical application.
We have compared all of this with each other, and although the test has not yet been completed, we have been able to see very interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws are perhaps even more "strict and perfect", but the actual application in Germany is better in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to establish new and more precise rules over and over again, and it is also necessary to look at the actual application of the law.
How can the project help you? What does this project mean to you?
It is precisely such joint control that could help us to stop constantly trying to perfect laws and reduce and balance thresholds if this does not seem to have a particularly positive effect.
Cost-effectiveness means acquiring a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But lowering thresholds for contracts does not guarantee that we will achieve this objective.
Perhaps it is even the case that in this way we are only burdening the system with excessive "paperwork", and those who are looking for gaps in the system have much easier to exploit the system than if the thresholds remained higher.
You are talking about the problems of the practical implementation of the Czech Public Procurement Act.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar authority to our NKÚ, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NKÚ is the Federal Court of Auditors, which is structured in a similar way to ours and also has a college, which is only slightly different. However, in principle both authorities work in a similar way.
The competences are also to some extent comparable, although Germany is a federal state, i.e. there are also these accounting offices in the individual federal states - in this the German system differs from ours.
The Federal Government can only control federal funds, which corresponds to our state resources.
Public funds, which are managed by the districts and municipalities, are subject to the control of the state accounting courts.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would hate to compare this without concrete information. Nevertheless, Germany is often described as a role model in some respects, but one certainly cannot say that Germany is better in everything.
Is that because the examiners are better there?
This is certainly not the case, but as I said, I do not like such comparisons.
It should also be noted that those countries that are a model for us also face problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have anything of cooperation with our authority, would they?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, how important was the amendment of the Procurement Act for your authority, do you already feel any effects?
In view of the fact that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had any effect on our tests.
Since our controls are carried out retrospectively, we have to expect a certain delay here.
So far, we have had more impact in the preparation phase of future controls - we have introduced the new control tool "Recognition of risks of inefficiency" and with this almost 14,000 public contracts have been examined and analysed - here, the changes will naturally have an impact, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, among other things.
Do you see the adoption of this law rather positive, or is the system burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "more stringent" and can no longer be complied with.
