The MVRDV architects prove that the real adventures are not only in the mind - using the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Büchenberg - 2 photos
"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there is something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the side of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician in a nearby large-scale company, says, "Yes, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
All have Internet, iPad and e-books.
No one goes to one of those old-style libraries today, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy city hardly in need of sightseeing at the gates of Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The municipality of 80,000 inhabitants has the lowest education rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
In order to counteract this stupid circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and to recreate the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro banknotes as nicely pinsed reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to master statistics: a library must come!
Winy Maas of Rotterdam's architecture firm MVRDV, master of bold bar charts and producer of witty, often cynical buildings, took the matter with familiar serenity and appeared for the competition hearing anno 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin in his face.
And while the jury was still staggering around and twitching with the armpits, the cheeky Maas piled his exquisite souvenirs to a pyramid by size and finished his actionistly supported speech with the words: "Dear Town Community!"
So this is him, my proposal for the Buchenberg of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain is poured out.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Büchenberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This makes the faceless small town retorte, which so far had no more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a stunned ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory to enrich a piece of contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The long way to the book
The first impression: Bucheldorado under cheese bell.
There is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, but the true pleasures of space and reading open up during the walking climb of topography.
The completely glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lamps clearly speak the language of a public city square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
You are already looking for park bench, dog and soccer playing boys and girls.
And books, books, books everywhere.
"Normally, the bookshelfs stand along the façade, and in the middle lies a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and turned the reading area from inside to outside.
The inside of the Buchenberg is cleverly used: in the middle are offices, internet library, chess club, environmental center and building technology center.
A special pleasure are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall covering, sometimes balustrade, sometimes stair railings.
Optics, feel and smell are foreign.
Even ingrained architects and civil engineers shake the head of the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, on request of the standard.
And so one day we found a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
For many years, a mm-thin plastic fleece has been used as a root pad in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
This is cheap and time-efficient.
The thin textile lasts one or two seasons, after which it is ripe for bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece was pressed to a thickness of four centimetres for the first time in these quantities.
Under heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, load-bearing material that smells a bit of new cars and a bit of sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the summit.
At the end of the almost 500-metre-long hiking tour, the Literaturcafé is not only rewarded with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They provide an atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literary mountains.
Donations for the new soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is a flagship project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
Heat and cool with geothermal energy.
Although the Buchenberg is under a glass lintel, even on sunny days the sun shines only briefly into the interior.
The wide wood bindings, which stand across to the glass façade, serve as shading and capture most of the sunlight.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest are fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial sceptic from the IT industry, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even describes Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "long overdue soul".
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal inventory.
For the time being, the optical gaps in the library - currently 70,000 pieces - are to be filled.
The concept has come to an end.
The shelves are filled to the top.
"Nothing is worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's just an ornament.
Thus, MVRDV succeeded in the royal discipline, which is called in the specialist jargon identity foundation.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert in US-European relations, Berlin is balancing it to a narrow diplomatic degree.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had initially signalled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This was eventually enforced by NATO.
Does Germany find it difficult to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is changing its foreign policy, away from a policy that has been managed, so to speak, by the US, towards a German foreign policy.
What is more, Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans thus find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe they are still approaching their role, but they are on the way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy such as France or Great Britain.
What exactly does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the attitude in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
Therefore, it must be careful not to push the public, but also the elites, into the heads of Arab countries.
It definitely does matter.
But I wouldn't want to give too much weight to this either, that's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that there is a great deal of understanding for the German position in Europe and even in the USA.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break, as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even show some respect for it.
After all, it signals that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be considered.
There are different opinions in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly declared itself in favour of veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration secretly has quite a lot of understanding for the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, publicly represent this position.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always appear.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu's politics.
Is it difficult for Germany to agree on its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a bit easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not the case at the moment.
So they can't be part of a broader line and instead have to push things out of their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of the relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive subject.
But I believe that the Germans are clear that they must play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player - does Germany want to play a leading role?
Or is it still difficult for Germany to lead?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
For example, if we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany takes on a greater role, various anti-German feelings become free.
It doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this way, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It must be receptive to a wide range of neighbours and opinions, and that is not easy.
Now the US's influence in European politics is steadily diminishing, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment, who else remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a greater role.
Even if they don't like it, they are uncomfortable and make them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America work together on the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Trademark protection" in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-renowned brand, Polo Ralph Lauren as well.
But what is Armani Polo?
Behind this lies a name officially registered in China, which has nothing to do with the original companies.
Nevertheless, it enjoys protection for as long as the actual namesakes do not complain.
And even then it is not clear whether they are right.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China," says Thomas Pattloch, attorney at Taylor Wessing, a law firm specializing in IPR violations in the Far East.
Every week, a new case lands on my desk.
A few additional letters are enough for the imitators to register their brands.
