Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and gonorrhea.
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papsilomaviruses, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Creepy lice and scabies are parasitic STIs.
Who are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and trippers are especially common among men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five of all cases of syphilis reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contacts between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonaden, candidiasis (fungal), trippers and human papsilomaviruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The spread of HIV among heterosexual adults in this country is comparatively low - nevertheless: about 20 percent of the HIV new infections are attributable to this group.
Among adolescents, chlamydia infections occur much more frequently than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people aged between 15 and 25.
Human papsilomaviruses are also common in adolescents in Germany.
How did the number of infections develop?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections more than doubled from 1697 in 2001 to 3698 in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been decreasing since 2007.
In 2011, there were around 2700 cases.
That's about a tenth less than the year before.
What symptoms indicate an STD?
Infectious diseases can cause genital ulcers, urination, discharge, abdominal pain and blisters or warts.
Often, however, they do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore remain unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not provide 100% protection.
In part, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed on through lubricating infections and close body contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations especially in frequently changing sex partners.
Most STIs can be diagnosed early and late consequences can be avoided.
