The prosecution tried on Friday to find out that the army-liberated Bradley Manning - accused of the greatest disclosure of confidential information in US history - missed several occasions to complain about the abuse he allegedly suffered in military custody.
During a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein stated that documents relating to weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month term in Quantico, Virginia had no complaints about his treatment.
One day before the cross-examination, which was held following a request by the defense to dismiss the charges - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the hard time in prison - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
At the hearing on Friday, Fein went through the forms with Manning, which officials had filled out after their meetings with Manning during his detention in the Quantico Military Prison, where he had been detained under increased prison conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had rated the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the facility as "very professional".
According to Fein, the forms did not contain any complaints about maltreatment, although officers had interviewed Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they had dealt with them, but they had not been recorded.
"They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) "No problems," and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he had mentioned a few months earlier on a form.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to have his observation status downgraded to "prevention of injuries".
The military declared that it had assigned him this restrictive status - which is one stage under the risk of suicide - to his and the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well and to get rid of the observation status to prevent injuries (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life from my point of view," said Manning.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Marine Base prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said that in Kuwait he had considered suicide and had once fainted due to the heat.
Not knowing what was happening to him or to the outside world was a burden.
"My world shrunk to Camp Arafjon, to this cage," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell - at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours - and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said that he had tried to keep moving, because it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
He always had to sleep with light that penetrated his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and guards couldn't see his face, they woke him up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to the treatment of Manning.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the Fort Leavenworth Military Prison, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned an accusation he had made in his statement on Thursday - so he had to sleep one night naked in his cell in Quantico and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners during a morning count.
Manning had testified that during this count he had never had the opportunity to wrap himself with his blanket.
During the interview on Friday, Manning stated that he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should have dropped the blanket with which he could have covered himself. However, he admitted that no one had asked him to.
On Thursday, Manning had testified that the previous night he was forced to sleep naked. He had previously tried to show an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning told the officer that he could have used the waistband of his underpants or flip-flops to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his prison experiences and drastically reduce his prison sentence if he is sentenced to trial before the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to minor offenses, while other charges considered too extreme are to be challenged.
The continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to justify the terms of detention.
The Pentagon maintains its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the regulations applicable to all prisoners under the highest security precautions in Quantico.
Charges against Manning include favoring the enemy, illegal publication of intelligence information on the Internet, the transmission of national defence information and the theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all counts, he is threatened with a life sentence.
