And then there's the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea in front of a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the conclusion that boredom can be defined as the experience of "desiring to do a satisfying job but not being able to do it".
Boredom therefore differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
In apathy, on the other hand, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, consists in "disturbing the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is passing slowly".
Boredom can almost sound like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored persons see the problem in their environment or in the world, while depressed persons see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored, even if we're just having trouble concentrating.
In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", for example: "The Inactive Mind: The Definition of Boredom from the Aspects of Attention", published in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a band on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud TV program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content. Others heard it at low volume, so it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
Those who heard the hard - to - hear television said that they were bored more than the other two groups - they had problems concentrating, could not find a reason for them, and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
When trying to focus on a difficult or strenuous task, the disturbance of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, Associate Professor of Neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you do a monotonous job - "like the search for defective products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help not to feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that zapping and scribble, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even fight them by keeping people more physically alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to walk around learn more and keep more information than those who are forced to sit still," Professor Fenske said.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a booming speaker, a particularly tiring film.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
In order to measure these differences, researchers developed in the 1980s a "scale of boredom susceptibility".
On the scale there are statements like "Many things I have to do, repeat themselves and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys get bored more often than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of Westflorida - especially in terms of the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty tense bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of adolescents were bored in school and doing homework, while 23% said they were bored when they were not in school.
But only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Today, 21 years later, Professor Larson says that he does not know whether the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he was sure that "youth was felt to be particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers did not have a great influence on their daily routine.
Back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases it causes people to take extreme physical risks and fall into gambling or drugs to alleviate them - studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors examine the relationship between boredom and creativity. Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades, is of this opinion.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else," says Gary Marcus, Professor of Psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn't always know what to do right now.
If you're bored and you use this energy to play and cook guitar, you'll be happy.
But while television can provide happiness in the short term, it disappears in the long run.
So if you pass an iPad to your bored child, you can get it away from boredom. However, it has not learned how to entertain or control yourself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "Self-control transfers from one situation to the other."
The child not only learns to talk, but also receives more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we view them too critically.
Instead, our goal should be to feel at home even outside of the constant activity and technology sprinkle.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we often have to be bored, but boredom is the agonizing, incessant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that in truth people are only looking for a way to turn off and relax.
"In an environment where we are constantly being overstimulated, it is difficult to deal with the noise once the noise has stopped."
