The most difficult profession in the world: the human working animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and their health if they carry 70 kilos of sulphur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by taking sulfur from the volcano Kawah Ijen in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he has to climb down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulphurous gas flowing out of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After he has broken out large sulfur stones that can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the sloping paths made of stone.
Although it is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes to climb at turtle pace, keeping the balance and carefully setting their steps so that they do not slip and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell on the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 Eurocents for every kilo of sulphur they mine.
Arriving at the top, they make their way between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and walk with the tiresome heavy baskets three kilometers to the Libra, which a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who since 1960 has used the deposits in the volcano and (never better said) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocents) for each kilo of sulphur.
She then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocents) each to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for producing matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even bleaching sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each way," explains Anto, who normally does three routes a day.
For each route he needs three hours, after which he is completely finished, but at the end of the day he has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
But what looks like a miserable wage for such a sheer inhuman effort is three times what he would earn with the field work.
"The daily wage of the miners here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid a day at the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, for a reason that is as important as sulphur in Indonesia: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hinduists, and I brought her to Java to convert her to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases.
27-year-old Anto has been risking his life at the Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulphur has already left his first traces, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for achieving his dream.
"I'm going to work here for two more years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French," he promises in more than just acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent but life-punished young man could work as a tourist guide, waiter or at the reception of a hotel, but instead he does the work of a stretcher.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other wearers and gets up every morning at two o'clock, because the sulfur also flows out at night, where its characteristic yellow color shines bluish in the darkness.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought from his own money.
About 400 carriers load the baskets with sulfur on their shoulders at the crater floor.
Despite its huge profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur mining to save costs and does not supply any equipment to the carriers who work on their own account and are paid for by weight.
You will also not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) surcharge per camera, which the guardians of this nature park together with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) require of the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human carrier.
"This work is for the animals and not for the human being," protests Madrusin, a stocky 42-year-old carrier who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he continues "as long as he can" because he needs the money to raise his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life.
Even when the sulfur burns the throat and the eyes itch, when the wind suddenly turns and the miners clamp into the thick columns that rise from the crater, the men are so hard that no one complains about serious diseases ... of course except the usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders that have deformed from the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on his back, Unainik, with his 53 years of age, is only able to carry 50 kg.
Every day he and his companions break 15 tons of sulphur from the volcano, which are transported by three trucks over a goat path between the bushes to the camp in Tamansari at a distance of 18 kilometers.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life," Unainik explains, opening his mouth wide, with some teeth missing.
Of his five children, the elder also works as a sulfur carrier at the age of 30.
Time passes, but poverty keeps generation to generation in one of the toughest occupations in the world: that of those who work as human donkeys at Kawah Ijen.
