So we thought, why don't we do something as creative as possible to tackle this problem, such as composing a rap?
1.2 children
Those who do not take this issue lightly are the government of Singapore.
Every year, it spends $1,300 on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But everything has had little success so far.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city state in Southeast Asia, known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
According to its national population authority, the birth rate is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time this rate was over 2 - which is also known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don't the Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Board, says this is due to "better education" and "greater career opportunities".
"This has enabled people to have much more options in terms of life goals and to set priorities than to marry and make a family," she explains.
These changes in social conditions have contributed to the increase in the number of single persons and to the delaying of marriage and births, the result of which is a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at a drastic increase in immigration to counteract the reduction of the population has led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where the barely disguised xenophobia against many new immigrants is flourishing, especially against the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons that the ruling party in Singapore achieved its worst result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While the falling birth rate has the known impact on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, health costs, and immigration policies, the example of Singapore also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to ensure that not so many small apartments are built.
It has already had an impact on the housing market.
The Urban Development Agency has begun to monitor the number of small apartments known as "shoe boxes" that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living area of 46 square meters and show a great sales success.
However, there is concern that they can promote the single person’s lifestyle, and that they discourage construction companies from building large homes for families.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of the real estate company EL Developers, says that his "shoe boxes" can be sold much faster than larger housing units.
They are so popular, and the units are sold out by days and even weeks faster than the larger units.
This makes them much better for our cash flow.
However, it admits that the new standards will give developers clearer orientations, which have previously been hampered if they want to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for an increase in the national birth rate, the talks with the Singaporeans working in the financial district show that they will not have a major impact.
"People are very stressed, the homes and education are expensive, which is why many put it off," says a young manager.
The children can have others.
"It's important for me to have my own money and time," says another man, about twenty years old.
Men and women cite their careers, stress and the cost of ownership and education as reasons why they cannot have children.
That is why the Singaporeans have the last word when it comes to having children - there is so much the government can do.
The offline private offline is private online
Privacy
According to the dictionary, this is the property of private or "that area of private life where one is entitled to protection from any kind of interference".
What is private for someone under the age of 16?
How is this definition applied to his everyday life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he faces when he makes known on the Internet situations that he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five young people between the ages of 10 and 15 who are often on the Internet.
In four of the cases, they associated the term with "something very personal" at the personal level and "to the password and the user" when they applied it to the social networks.
"I wouldn't disclose my deepest secrets in a post," says 10-year-old Jorge, trying to explain the meaning of "private" in websites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has accounts for two years.
"These are very confidential secrets, my mother is allowed to know them, but not the whole world," he confirms.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures of games.
I also spend my time with acquaintances.
"I wouldn't share a photo that isn't mine, or someone who makes the fool," he says.
The boy is aware that it is wrong to post obscene photos, naked photos, crimes, or offensive or violent comments.
Jorge assures to know 35 friends he has in FB and nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Including the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I signed up on Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if someone answers me, I'm just uploading it," he adds.
"The social networks are entertaining, I can quickly talk to relatives in the distance or with friends," he says.
When asked, he answers that he would never accept an invitation from an unknown person.
Even if someone approached him with a stranger, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask. In Ask, he admits not to know 20 of the people he has added to his friends list.
"That doesn't scare me because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to the boy, no one has made any suggestions or asked him for his address or phone number.
"If someone pushes me or demands them from me, I simply remove them from my user account," he admits.
José contacted Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not unknown to experiences known today as cyberbullying.
A friend's friend was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never found out who it was," he assures.
According to José, the victim didn't close the account.
"He only did it privately."
He then explains a number of steps to configure a user account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, that's what I'd do if he was unsympathetic or if I wanted to get rid of him.
"But I know this is cyberbullying," he explains.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, English teacher with a university degree in education and learning, believes that in order to orientate children and young people, it must be understood that it is the purpose of social networks to inform.
"The Internet emerged as a medium for searching for information, but with the publication of these pages the rules of the game have changed," she says.
Porras explains that the academic Marc Prensky, holder of a master's degree in pedagogy at Yale University and author of the work "Digital Natives and Immigrants", formed these terms to explain the phenomenon.
They are the digital natives, the children and young people who grew up with this technology.
"We're the digital immigrants they're supposed to teach when we're still learning," he says.
He explains that this is a complex issue, "because we require them to have a defined criterion on what can be disseminated, published or said, at an age where maturity is not sufficient."
"They should also be selective if they want to be popular, have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," he adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and adolescents what privacy is is to ask them questions that make them think.
"Telling you not to do it doesn't work," he says.
Porras then calls some possibilities: There are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger. Then why do you do it on the Internet?
Or: Would you like to have a photo of you published, like the one you published from a friend?
Do you know what the others publish about you?
Did you ask the other people for permission before you labeled photos of celebrations?
And one more question: Do everyone need to know what you're doing at any moment?
Another point is to give them to understand that they need to act online as they do offline.
They're the same rules.
"Someone outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to social networks," he explains.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teacher and educator, comments that it is essential that parents carefully read the guidelines of social networks.
When they understand all the sections, they have solid foundations to talk to their children about the importance of opening a user account on the Internet.
"For example, age, or what you can share or publish," he explains.
According to Guardia, the children must be reminded of the lesson "Don't talk to strangers."
Conclusion of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and was supposed to be signed theoretically by the seven governments present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur. Sources in the State and Presidential Chancellery initially announced that they would hand it over after the retreat, but then explained that it would be published on the Peruvian government's website at some time.
When asked about the text, they stated that the content was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information on the summit was limited at all times.
During the day only the image of the presidential meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulating among journalists was received by the press spokespersons of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, causing discomfort among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Afterwards, the President of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the Humala Declaration and not the official document at the end of the summit.
Last October Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and even on this occasion the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was not published, despite a strong press call.
On the official ASPA website, you can see that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems were in place for journalists, but to a large extent they restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a ruling by the Court of Justice of The Hague, which resolves a border conflict between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the ICJ, which begins on Monday in The Hague, in the trial Lima initiated against Santiago to listen to the pleas of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the verdict on the differences we are currently bringing before this international court," said Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and remains a country that adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to the international courts," Piñera adds and greeted Humala with a handshake against the flags of both countries.
Both Presidents confirmed that they would submit to the ICJ after Colombia had brought an action against the Bogotá Agreement following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered to be a serious mistake, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this international court.
The summit was attended by the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from Unasur since 2011 after the resignation of its President Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and concluded the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The head of state read the final document, in which it announced that 16 decisions were taken and that the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set for a total investment of 17 billion dollars.
Regarding the decisions taken, he said that the countries of Unasur "will take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we extend the decisions on residence rights."
He announced that measures would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised transnational crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant features, but rather serve to expand our production output and to show our peoples a better future," added Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving spatial connections in South America, especially in rural and border areas... thus uniting our countries and opening up new economic forms," said the Peruvian President in a read-out statement.
Among these projects would also be five Peruvians, who would be on the transversal axes of his territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which would provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he did not give any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its resumption in the Union of South American Nations" from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and good neighbourly relations was another aspect highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before beginning his participation in the regional meeting that he expected a meeting with his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico, in order to treat the maritime conflict respectfully according to a verdict of the ICC questioned by Bogotá.
"Maybe tomorrow (Saturday) I will meet President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We will review all these ways - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also requires talks with Nicaragua," he underlined.
"I hope to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectfully as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the inauguration of the new president of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the Defence Ministers of the bloc also met in advance to adopt the 2013 Plan of Action to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, even if the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru presides over the regional bloc.
"South America must learn to integrate its citizens," says Rafael Correa.
The President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, today confirmed that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal, whereby "South America can actually learn something from Europe."
Correa, who participated in the 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Lima, declared to state television in Peru that Europeans "killed themselves in World War II and other conflicts" and "are now practically a fatherland."
In this sense, he defended the project of creating a South American citizenship that would advance the member states of Unasur.
"The free movement of citizens and workers must be achieved in all South American countries, as is already the case in the Andean community; however, there are still reactionary sectors that want to return to the past," he warned.
The President of Ecuador also supported the reorganization of the Organization of American States (OEA) with the aim of reducing the influence of Anglo-Saxon states and taking into account those who have signed the San José Convention on Human Rights.
Those who teach never commit themselves to anything, and in return we sign the South Americans always everything.
"It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights has its headquarters in Washington and is financed by the United States," he said as an allusion to the political asylum that Ecuador has granted to the founder of WikiLeaks, Julian Assange.
Correa assured him that he did not regret this decision because it did not betray his principles, but followed his "deep democratic values and views on human rights".
He added that there were "reasoned assumptions at the time that Assange would be extradited to a third country and that his procedure would not be complied with."
He also criticized the Swedish judiciary, which had asked him to interrogate him on his territory for alleged sexual offences, while "Swedish jurisprudence allowed this by means of a video conference that could have been carried out via Ecuador's embassy in London."
Correa explained that there was a risk that Assange's health and mental condition would be affected.
"Since he was in our embassy, I haven't spoken to him, but the ambassador has informed me that he has a slight problem with the lungs, but not a serious one," said Ecuador's head of state.
There is, however, a danger that he would suffer physical and psychological damage because he was trapped in a confined space and could not perform physical exercises outdoors.
"This would affect everyone's health," he added.
Correa stated that the solution to the asylum granted to Assange since June at the Embassy of Ecuador in London was the granting of a licence to travel to Ecuador, and that this was in the hands of Great Britain, Sweden and the legal authorities of Europe. He underlined that there had been talks with London to find a solution for the imprisoned founder of WikiLeaks.
We do not deal with human rights, we do not use that word in this case, but there have been constant discussions.
"The solution to this problem lies in the hands of the United Kingdom, Sweden and the European legal authorities, because the lawyer of Assange, Baltazar Garzón, conducts a series of proceedings on various European bodies," he said.
And "when Britain grants this charter tomorrow, I think it's done."
And if Sweden interrogated Mr. Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy in London or via Skype, as Swedish jurisprudence allows and in other cases was done, the problem would be solved.
Correa took the opportunity to confirm himself as a defender of press freedom and said that what he did not tolerate were "the mediocrity, the evil intention and the lie that invalidated freedom of expression."
"The biggest enemies of press freedom are not the evil and perverse politicians, but bad journalists who seek and blackmail profit," he said.
In this sense, he congratulated Ecuador for not being dominated by such journalists "and not by bankers or hegemonic and petty-bourgeois countries," and anticipated that, in a re-election, he "will deepen the revolution in order to continue the path in this right direction."
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto against Paraguay in Unasur at least until his next elections, arguing that the organism "must remain hard and not allow any opportunism and no coup d'état disguised as legal" because it "destructed the legitimacy of democracy in Paraguay."
The President of Ecuador also considers the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to be "absolutely justified" now and after the ruling of the International Court of Justice of The Hague, which favoured the maritime sovereignty of Nicaragua to negotiate the maritime borders between the two countries with Nicaragua.
At present, this judgment is not being implemented.
It is a problem between a South American and a Central American state.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome in the pursuit of a common path.
They must be treated comprehensively so that they can be overcome and looked forward.
He also relied on a good conclusion of the disputes over the maritime borders between Peru and Chile before the same court and said that "it is right for Latin America to appeal to international authorities if both countries commit themselves to accept the verdict, even if it is very harsh."
With regard to the possibility of being a candidate for the next presidential elections in Ecuador to achieve his third consecutive mandate, he stated that he saw this opportunity "with much optimism and joy, although sometimes it is very difficult."
Correa assured that if he lost the February 2013 elections, he would retire from political life.
I have never personally been interested in power, but under such unjust circumstances as in Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement had the belief that it was I who guaranteed this probable victory, so I have to shoulder this responsibility," he said.
If I were to win, it would be my last period as president, after which I withdraw from public life.
This also applies if we lose.
"That's decided," he explained.
Correa also referred to the treatment of the health problems of the president of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, in Cuba.
I have just spoken to Vice-President of Venezuela Nicolás Maduro, who told me that he had travelled there for a planned, routine treatment and that he would be expected to be able to travel back to Cuba after the election campaign.
"In no case does it mean a relapse in the health of President Chávez," he commented.
The Ecuadorian Head of State attended today in Lima the 6th Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), which ended with the call for greater regional integration to ensure sustainable progress, equality and security.
The cause of dying because of AIDS today is too late detection
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed with the results of the investigation: HIV positive.
"It was as if a bomb hit," he says about the moment he received the diagnosis that the doctor tried "to weaken" without any apparent success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to learn about it; and this with such dedication that he was celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), in which he came after several fights in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was difficult to imagine at the beginning of the 1990s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmata.
At that time, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye "because it led to a dead end."
At that time AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today it is possible to survive this syndrome with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic who know nothing about their disease and where the virus has already done harm and exhausted their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the occurrence of the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who receives treatment in time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of HCG's HIV unit, saying that this information was supported by a prestigious scientific publication in April this year.
The expert on infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva, commented that the scientists concluded since 2008 that AIDS was not a death sentence, but that the years of survival and quality of life depended on the degree of impairment of the immune system of individuals at the start of treatment, and that those who are not addicted to drugs had greater chances: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years with a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above remarks mean that those who receive the diagnosis HIV-positive at the age of 25 can, in this sense, "become 75 years old without problems as long as they are under control," said this expert.
In order to properly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Even if mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (ONUSIDA Annual Report), it is still true that 60 percent of the patients registered in the national database have died since the advent of AIDS.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and by May of this year there are already 187 deaths; however, it is assured that universal access to antiretroviral medicines has been available since 2005.
- So why do people still die from it?
- In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so is our hospital.
At least in the past 12 years, we have not had any drug supply problems. The problem is that people come in a far advanced state because they do not know their infection condition, i.e. in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have an accompanying infection. In order to be able to influence global mortality, more early diagnoses are required, which is why all persons requiring this need massive detection tests."
The experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (State Committee on AIDS Prevention in Jalisco) and also the patients such as Fabrizio, who had his test carried out at a private laboratory, for the sole reason that he had made a friend of his who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had the Kaposi sarcoma (a cancer-like tumor), which is one of the usual complications.
Everything's different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die and don't want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, I prefer to burst three times," they say in my case.
The change was to improve, I eat well, exercise and take the medication.
Today, all his parents know is that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, do a lot of work, have an active but responsible sex life, I pay attention to my health and that of the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO to encourage with his testimony those who are afraid today in the context of the worldwide AIDS day.
They should take the test if they belong to the risk group. The earlier they know if they are HIV positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like all people.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are big holes between the health programs and the ordinary citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, journalist from Guadalajara, who has taken care of the cause of HIV.
And the most important thing is prevention.
In the designated places, "the distribution of condoms was actually increased; previously they were delivered individually, now they give us packets with a hundred pieces, which is good, but there are still people who do not have access to a condom," he said.
Young people are at risk for new infections.
"What do you need them for?" is a widespread mockery question of social workers, orientation staff in schools, employees in pharmacies and in the health care system, which young people do not want to expose themselves to, the correspondent assured.
He suggested reorienting this inefficient distribution; the condoms should be located not only behind the counter, but in public toilets in public toilets of facilities frequented by young people.
Promiscuity should not be promoted.
They are not to be paid for the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González replied to the question of whether there would be a distribution of reserves under his administration.
"Sexuality does not look like this; it is best to bring the condoms closer to those who are already engaged in sexual activity," he put it to the point.
Key Jalisco figures
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state is in fourth place nationally, new and cumulated AIDS cases, and 13th place in terms of HIV.
92% of the infections occur via sexual intercourse, 6% via blood and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV because for each registered case there are 4 or 5 people who do not know it.
After the United States Court of Appeal has confirmed a ruling that does not recognise the restructuring of the liabilities of the Vitro Group reached through a trade dispute in Mexico, a disastrous precedent will be created for any national company with subsidiaries in the neighbouring country that has payment problems.
One could say, then, that the procedures for the survival of companies that allow Mexican laws are not valid in the land of the stars and stripes, contrary to international agreements.
In practice, the recognition of the verdict given on June 15 by Judge Harlin Hale at the Bancarrotas Court for the northern district of Texas leads Mexican companies to be helplessly seized of their property beyond the Bravo River.
However, the decision opens the door to the largest glass manufacturer in Mexico to appeal to the Supreme Court of the United States for three inconsistencies.
While the judge points out that the creditors must be subject to the bankruptcy law of the United States, the court of appeal of the Fifth Circuit, based in New Orleans, first of all says that the main proceedings are the trade dispute dealt with in Mexico.
The first point would mean that international cooperation in insolvency proceedings for companies with a cross-border profile is not known.
Indeed, to this end, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Trade Law was created, using the American Law Institute as a mediator.
Secondly, the judgment states that, without the votes of the companies, the majority required for the restructuring of the liabilities would not have been achieved after recognition of the liabilities in the bankruptcy assets held by the branches of Vitro with its parent company.
However, this possibility is recognized by Mexican laws.
In fact, vitro is not the first case in which this scheme has been approved.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose liabilities were confirmed by the Instituto Federal de Concursos Mercantiles (Bundesinstitut für Handelskonkurs) among companies in the group.
It is also true that after the withdrawal of the votes of the branches, the creditors of Vitro, the creditors who sued Vitro in the United States courts, i.e. the vultures funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have reached a majority.
