Every semester, when the professor of religion decided to hold a course on the end of the world, he knew that he had an irresistible fishing hook: the end of the Mayan calendar's "long reverse count" on 21 December, which many people believed meant the end of the world.
But Charmé had no idea what to expect in the following two months: the destructive hurricane Sandy, which some called "Deudarmaggedon", and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place from which Christian theorists believe the Apocalypse begins.
"I didn't realize that this would be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé said this week to the students at Rutgers-Camden University, New Jersey.
