And he is not the only professor who is offering courses on the "end of the world" this semester, which should actually be the last in history.
In Temple, the associate professor Barry Vacker gives the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World."
Every week, the students investigate apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, virus and germs, and global warming.
"We analyze why these ideas spread over time," he said, as well as the way hypothetical scenarios are offered that lead to a certain human behavior.
For example, if nuclear material gets into the hands of terrorists, a war could break out.
This month, the students analyzed films with apocalyptic content and examined how they could be compared to real life.
"I tried to inform the students about what is possible, likely, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
